courses.learning_outcomes:
After completing this course, students should be able to

- strengthen the generic skills that include cognitive and intellectual skills (critical analysis and integrate knowledge etc.);
- acquire specific knowledge and skills in financial accounting;
- have a good understanding about the analysis and interpretation of financial statements;
- compare the differences between Hong Kong standards and International Accounting Standards.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:
- Understand the relationship between AIS and the organization’s business processes;
- Document a company’s business processes;
- Apply key concepts and skills required to analyse, design, build and maintain an AIS;
- Manage enterprise risks from an information system perspective;
- Evaluate major business processes and make control recommendation;
- Examine and evaluate new opportunities and challenges brought about by technological developments.

After completing this course, students should be able to:
(CLO 1) appreciate the significance of business ethics and corporate social responsibility in contemporary business environment;
(CLO 2) understand the principles of business entrepreneurship and its significance in the business economy in Hong Kong and the Mainland;
(CLO 3) compile a business plan to start up a business (or enhance existing business) providing innovative yet feasible business solutions through an integration of business and accounting knowledge in a capstone project;
(CLO 4) demonstrate effective oral and written communication skills in presenting business problems and solutions.

By the end of the course, students will be able to
(1) understand theories and analystical techniques for guiding corporate accounting and financial decision making;
(2) find this course highly relevant if they pursue a career in accounting, auditing, financial analysis, corporate finance, investment banking, or management consulting.

The objectives of the course are to:

1. allow students to understand the unique structure of entities in the financial services industry;
2. equip students with an understanding of industry-specific financial reporting standards such as HKFRS 9 *Financial Instruments* and HKFRS 17 *Insurance Contracts*;
3. strengthen students’ awareness on the risk disclosure requirements under HKFRS 7 *Financial Instrument: Disclosures*; and
4. allow students to interpret the industry-specific financial statements and perform basic financial statement analysis.

1. To learn and evaluate current principles of financial accounting;
2. To apply generally accepted accounting principles to situations involving the recording of transactions and the preparation of financial statements;
3. To read and critically evaluate financial statements;
4. To consider the larger context of financial reporting (beyond rules and procedures), including how company executives and financial analysts view financial reporting;
5. To evaluate accounting issues from a global perspective;
6. To identify and respond effectively to professional accounting ethical issues.

On completion of this course, students will be able to:
ILO1. understand basic cost concepts and product costing techniques;
ILO2. analyze and evaluate management accounting issues in a critical manner;
ILO3. develop solution for business and accounting problems;
ILO4. apply Management Accountants’ Codes of Ethics to resolve an ethical issue;
ILO5. demonstrate a proficiency of oral communication in a professional setting; and
ILO6. work efficiently and effectively in teams to solve business and accounting problems.

After completing this course, students should be able to:
1. Analyse the client activities, industry, economic and fiscal environment, and the impact of identified risks on the overall statutory audit plan as well as on individual accounts and assertions;
2. Design audit procedures including tests of controls, substantive procedures and analytical procedures in relation to specific accounts and assertions;
3. Identify, discuss and draft the appropriate auditors’ report to be issued in specific situations;
4. Have an awareness of legal liability and responsibilities to various stakeholders relying on the audit and audit report.

After completing this course, students will be able to:
1. Understand the principles of Hong Kong Taxation;
2. Compute the tax payable under property tax, salaries tax, profits tax, personal assessment & stamp duty;
3. Develop basic tax planning techniques;
4. Demonstrate proficiency in written communication in a professional setting;
5. Apply accounting and other business knowledge to develop solutions to complex business problems.

The objectives of the course are to:

* Access WRDS and other databases to extract useful data;
* Perform data processing and cleaning procedures using SAS/Stata;
* Understand the basics of fraud detection with accounting data;
* Perform basic predictions of the company's sales, earnings, and cash flow;
* Form portfolios using accounting based trading strategies.

Upon completing this course, students should be able to understand and know well the open economy and relevant financial management and investment theories, and make application to the current financial management operations and capital market investment practices.

1. Understand the macroeconomic and financial linkages;
2. Understand the international monetary system;
3. Know well cross-border asset liability management and carry trade;
4. Understand exchange rate determination theories and practices;
5. Know well multinational exchange rate risks and management;
6. Know well global asset allocation;
7. Know well financial market investment management;
8. Know well cross-border M&A investment.
